Japan's traditional mountain village of Shirakawa-go is known for its fast-disappearing building style called gassho-zukuri. As one of the snowiest places in the country, the characteristic farmhouses were built with thickly thatched and steeply slanting roofs. Many date to around 1800 or earlier and are still lived in today, although many farming families (together with those from the nearby village of Gokayama) have now turned to tourism, welcoming visitors (most arriving via Takayama) to spend the night in their unique homes.

Today, December 6, is the feast day of #StNick or #StNicholas -  best known globally as the historical inspiration for #SantaClaus - a 4th-century bishop of #Myra (today modern day #Demre in Turkey). Lots of events will take place today at the 6th-century Church of St Nicholas built atop the foundations of an earlier church where he served as bishop. It is believed that the tomb that held his bones - before they were stolen and taken to Bari, Italy in the 11th century - was discovered below the existing church in 2022. St. Nicholas is the #patronsaint of Russia, and this church is a popular pilgrimage site for all Orthodox Christians and Santa lovers from around the world.

#Taktsang or #TigersNest is the defining image of the small #Himalaya nation of #Bhutan looking like it came straight from a tourist's dream book. It is known as the #sacred site where a #Buddhist master is said to have arrived on the back of a flying tiger in the 8th century. Visitors today make the 4-5 hour trek round-trip that is steep (but not impossible) to a 17th century temple miraculously perched 900 m above the floor of the #Paro Valley (and 3000 m above sea level). It is breathtaking in every sense of the word!

Visitors heading from Brussels to Bruge will regret bypassing #Ghent - an even closer and more convenient daytrip, just 50 minutes by train from Brussels. It boasts a rich #medieval history, beginning with the imposing 12th-century #GravensteenCastle - one of the largest and best preserved moated #castles in Europe. Built and used as the fortified residence of the Counts of Flanders until 1353 and later re-purposed as an intimidating court, prison (its tales of torture are legendary), mint, and even as a cotton factory.

They live almost exclusively in the Southern Hemisphere: only one species, the Galápagos penguin, is found north of the Equator.
